06608nam a22009735i 9780271089737DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20212021pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710897377 a10.1515/97802710897372doi  a(DE-B1597)583781  a(OCoLC)1237397815  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBL51b.R466 2021 7aLAN0150002bisacsh04a21022300aResponding to the Sacred :bAn Inquiry into the Limits of Rhetoric /ced. by Kyle Jensen, Michael Bernard-Donals. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (286 p.) :b8 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart 1. Sacred Encounters -- t1 Sacred Passages, Rhetorical Passwords -- t2 Engaging a Rhetorical God -- t3 Political Theologies of Sacred Rhetoric -- t4 How to Undo Truths with Words -- t5 Chanting the Supreme Word of Information -- tPart 2. Sacred Practices -- t6 Hacking the Sacred (or Not) -- t7 Divining Rhetoric’s Future -- t8 Where Is the Nuclear Sovereign? -- t9 From the Cathedral to the Casino -- t10 Rightness in Retrospect -- t11 Historiography and the Limits of (Sacred) Rhetoric -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith language we name and define all things, and by studying our use of language, rhetoricians can provide an account of these things and thus of our lived experience. The concept of the sacred, however, raises the prospect of the existence of phenomena that transcend the human and physical and cannot be expressed fully by language. The sacred thus reveals limitations to rhetoric.Featuring essays by some of the foremost scholars of rhetoric working today, this wide-ranging collection of theoretical and methodological studies takes seriously the possibility of the sacred and the challenge it poses to rhetorical inquiry. The contributors engage with religious rhetorics—Jewish, Jesuit, Buddhist, pagan—as well as rationalist, scientific, and postmodern rhetorics, studying, for example, divination in the Platonic tradition, Thomas Hobbes’s and Walter Benjamin’s accounts of sacred texts, the uncanny algorithms of Big Data, and Hélène Cixous’s sacred passages and passwords. From these studies, new definitions of the sacred emerge—along with new rhetorical practices for engaging with the sacred.This book provides insight into the relation of rhetoric and the sacred, showing the capacity of rhetoric to study the ineffable but also shedding light on the boundaries between them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aHoly, ThexPhilosophy. 0aRhetoric. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh  aReligion.  aRhetoric.  aRitual.  aSacred.1 aBallif, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernard-Donals, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernard-Donals, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBessette, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConner, Trey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoyle, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrank, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGross, Daniel M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaynes, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJensen, Kyle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJensen, Kyle, eeditor.4edt